# Commit Message Style

When generating a git commit message for this repository, follow these rules strictly:

## Format

`<file/topic>: <verb> <description>.`

- Start the description with a lowercase verb: add, fix, update, remove, extend, rename, move, refactor.
- Max 72 characters total for the subject line.
- Always end with a period.
- Be terse. No filler words.
- Subject only by default. Do NOT add a body unless something is non-obvious (constraint, workaround, intentional deviation).

## Topic naming

- Single file: use the filename without extension. Example: `user.dto: add eduEmail field to StudentInformation.`
- Long file names: glob-style shortening. Example: `backfill.status.*command.handler: fix race condition.`
- Multiple files in same area: glob or topic name. Example: `change.student.program.*: extend self-serve validations.`
- Use spaces, not slashes, in multi-word topics. Example: `test utils: add fixture helpers.` (not `test/utils:`)

## Initial commits

- Brand-new file or component: `<file>: initial commit.`
- Brand-new module with multiple files: `<module>: initial commit.`

## Good examples

- `user.dto: add eduEmail field to StudentInformation.`
- `chatApi: extend sendMessage to support attachments.`
- `conversation list: add loading state.`
- `change.student.program.*: extend self-serve validations.`
- `MessagesList: initial commit.`

## Bad examples (do NOT produce these)

- `Add mock chat API functions and data for conversations and messages` — missing topic prefix, capitalized verb, no period, filler words.
- `feat(api): add sendMessage` — do not use Conventional Commits prefixes; this repo uses the topic:verb format.
- `user.dto: Added eduEmail field.` — past tense and capitalized verb, both forbidden.
